with Sansão (local guide). Birds recorded during morning and afternoon. Morning: trilha da Madeirinha on the right bank of the Madeirinha river. Afternoon: river trip downstream on the Roosevelt to see Perneta, an impressive Black Caiman which comes for handouts. Light rain prior to departure (from 04h30 to 05h50), and again in mid-afternoon (15h15 to 16h25).
Historical checklist created by eBird/Macaulay Library from Internet Bird Collection media. Original IBC location name and coordinates: Pousada Rio Roosevelt (-8.4943, -60.9623).

with Sansão (local guide). Left by 05h30 for the Trilha do Ouro, on the left bank of the Roosevelt at the head of the Cachoeira da Gloria. Very hot and humid, and things were mostly quiet but it was still quite productive overall -- back a little earlier than other days (to the lodge by 12h00). After lunch I had a sit-in waiting for the weather to decide one way or the other. The rain held off, so I ventured onto the trail I dubbed "5k". Back by 18h00.

with Sansão (local guide). Left at 05h35 for the Perneta trail, roughly 20 minutes downstream from the pousada on the right/east bank of the Roosevelt. The trail is about 1.5 km total and it makes a loop through wonderful vine and heliconia forest. We birded here until mid-day, stopping briefly at a saleiro on the way back. After lunch, left again at 15h35 for the Jacamin trail a short ways downstream on the right bank. We cut this trail short since it looked like it was going to rain, and spent the final 45 minutes of light checking out the scrubby rock and sand-bars.

with Sansão (local guide). Hit the trails by 05h30, walking the Mirante (or as I had called it, the 5k trail) trail. A nice trail, but not terribly active in comparison to bird activity on the preceding days, and quite hot and quiet by 10h30. We walked about 3km before cutting to the river's edge where a boat was waiting for us. Back a little before noon. Early afternoon spent around the lodge with Edson Endrigo and the principals of World Wildlife Images. Left to head upriver by 15h30 to look for Bamboo Antshrike. Sansão wanted to check out a picada on the left bank of the Roosevelt upstream from the mouth of the Madeirinha, and after I get a single photo of a Dwarf Tyrant-Manakin the skies opened, soaking us.

with Sansão (local guide). Birds recorded on the Trilha Ronca (ca. 20 minutes upstream from the lodge on the right bank of the Roosevelt), which I birded until 12h30. I reached the far side of a higher, flat area past the creek which the trail follows, before turning back - the trail is roughly 3.5 km long and has fantastic birding potential.----After lunch at the lodge I took a walk on my own on the trail to the tower and all the way to the head of the airstrip, which I followed back to the lodge.

with Sansão (local guide) in morning, then together with Sansão, Semí, and Edson Endrigo and his group in the afternoon. Distances traveled not certain, thus the list is being recorded as incidental. ----Back to the Trilha da Ronca this morning, some 25 minutes upstream on the Roosevelt. Walked its entire length (ca. 3km) and back, all was rather quiet. Then in the afternoon joined up with Edson to walk the Trilha do Socó.

with Sansão (local guide). Distance covered wasn't recorded, so the list is being entered as incidental. Santa Maria trail (upstream on the right bank of the Roosevelt) in the morning, then the lodge clearing and the Madeirinha river in the afternoon.

with Sansão (local guide). The usual schedule. We headed downstream today to the Trilha da Esperança, which we birded from 05h45 to 12h30, reaching perhaps 200m beyond the big leafcutter ant colony. We spent a good part of the early morning around the dry igarapé working a Zigzag Heron (actually 3 or more birds), trying to digi-scope the birds. In the afternoon we tried upstream by boat, checking out the arm of the river just above the airstrip where there was a dead pirarara attracting vultures. Then it was up to the meeting of the Madeirinha and the Roosevelt, and then to the mouth of a lagoon - a short distance upstream from there is the spot for Bamboo Antshrike, in high tangles of slender vines, but the bird wasn't home. Back at the lodge by 18h00.

with Sansão (local guide). Left by 05h35 en route to the large saleiro/barreiro below the Cachoeira do Inferninho, which we birded from 06h15 to 11h30. A good selection of mammals, and some nice views of some parrtos coming down to ingest minerals. After the afternoon rain (to 16h00), we birded the track to the upstream port, and I checked out the airstrip for a bit.

species_comments: heard only, but certainly more than just a single pair. As we were to find at the campinas, the species is remarkably common along the Cujubim.

trip_comments: with Alan Bolten, Karen Bjorndal, Semí from Pousada Rio Roosevelt. Birds recorded on the boat trip upstream on the Roosevelt from the lodge's upstream port to the mouth of the Igarapé Cujubim.

with Alan Bolten and Karen Bjorndal, Semí (local guide). Birds recorded at the barreiro (clay lick) inside the forest downstream from the Inferninho rapids on the left bank of the Roosevelt. There was still a reasonable amount of water covering the parts of the barreiro we couldn't see, and the mud was deep in some spots that we could watch. The hoped-for Tapir didn't materialize, but a big highlight was a herd of 50+ White-lipped Peccaries which arrived in mid-morning to consume clay at the lick while we watched at close range. In late morning as we were finally deciding to leave, the Crimson-bellied Parakeets finally dropped down to the ground for their fill of mud.

with Karen Bjorndal, Alan Bolten, Semí from the lodge. Birds recorded on the Campinas do Cujubim trail, my first visit to this trail, which I found to be an excellent access to the rocky campina and campinarana habitats. The trail passes through a very short stretch of campinarana before entering a rocky (sandstone) campina which is quite extensive. Worth noting that the Cujubim is said to be too shallow to navigate by August/September, which means the trail would be out of range during the lowest water season.
species_comments: remarkable numbers, possibly the most I've ever seen of the species at a single site in a morning. Count is exact, but undoubtedly undercounted as some groups may have passed overhead without vocalizing while we looked at other things. Birds were flying out of an area of taller campinarana in the direction of the Cujubim (which they passed over), perhaps en route to the Roosevelt to feed. Consisted of pairs and groups of 4 - 6 birds.

trip_comments: From my notebook: "From 0540 to 0825 on the entrance track in foggy conditions (eventually clearing up), then after breakfast Jessica and I checked out the barranca path and then the lagoa. Water levels are high, and the barrance is under water. Apparently at this time of year there is no problem passing the corredeiras without getting out of the boat. I walked a short distance along the old boat track, spending plenty of time watching some flowering Inga trees. This track had overgrown some and needs to be cleared up. Back by 1220. After lunch I birded from 1405 to 1640 on the trail behind the pousada. From 1640 to dusk in the lodge clearing.

From my notes: "Birded the entrance track and 'boat track' from 05h45 to 11h45, with an hour for breakfast and a brief rest. After lunch I headed out alone to bird the revised trail through transitional forest and then the entrance track - the trailhead is on the entrance road - from 14h35 to 17h25.

Birds recorded at Pousada Rio Azul during a visit with a Terra da Gente film crew. --Birded entrance track from 05h30 to 07h00. Then walked the Old Boat track until maybe 11:00 - 11:30 or so, getting soaked in the process. After lunch we filmed an interview and many takes of me walking back and forth. Later on I watched a Tapajos Hermit lek for a while, before wandering into the woods to try to track down Bald Parrot.

Observations while guiding Gordon Ellis and Ian Ellis. Checklist lacks required effort information. AM birded entrance track to the Jatobá Trail. PM birded 'Spadebill trail' and returned to the lodge via the Jatobá Trail; we checked out the stream behind the lodge, then finished the afternoon in the lodge clearing.

Observations while guidin Gordon Ellis and Ian Ellis. Checklist lacks required effort information. AM we birded the neighbouring 'Fazenda do Osmar', in the afternoon we birded the Jatobá Trail, the lagoa, and made a trip downriver on the rio Azul.

Birds recorded while guiding Jeffrey Peter, Richard Chute, and John Deppman. Checklist lacks required effort information. ----Birded lodge clearing, Lagoa, Old Boat Trail in the morning (it rained during part of the morning). In the afternoon we birded the lodge clearing, the Boundary Trail, the lodge clearing again (in the rain), and the entrance road.

Birds recorded while guiding Jeffrey Peters, John Deppman, and Richard Chute. Required effort information lacking.----We birded the lodge clearing, the entrance road, and the Jatobá loop in the morning. In the afternoon we birded the lodge clearing, the Lagoa, and then walked the entrance track after dark.
with David and Susanne Cohen, Jim and Susan Graham. Lodge clearing to 09h00, then entrance track returning via Boundary trail, then area around boat landings. PM around lodge clearing.
with David and Susanne Cohen, Jim and Susan Graham. Entrance road and Jatobá trail in the morning, Nascentes trail in the afternoon.

Traveled downriver on the rio Azul in 2 boats with 5 pax each, including the pilots (Carlão and Adão) and myself. We mostly drifted, reaching the point where the water starts to speed up a little before the 1st corredeira. Returned doing a little bit of spotlighting in the early evening.----Weather: mostly clear, sunny with scattered clouds including a couple of heavy-looking ones. It rained in the evening, from 19h30 to 20h45.

with Kevin Zimmer. Birds recorded on the entrance track to the edge of the pastures. Activity was quite low at first, but as the sun hit the habitat and things warmed up a little, activity certainly picked up accordingly.

with Kevin Zimmer. Most of the early morning before departure for Alta Floresta spent in the lodge clearing, though we also made the shortest of forays into the forest along the kitchen trail and the Schistocichla trail.

with Kevin Zimmer. Birds noted around the lodge clearing and on the walk down to the river's edge, also at porto while Carlão finished getting the boat ready.

Manhã intensa de Birding na pousada rio azul. Iniciamos nossa atividade ainda de madrugada nas imediações da pousada. Após o café, descemos o rio azul de barco, com o motor desligado, por cerca de 4 km. Entramos na trilha da ponte, contornando a divisa da pousada com uma fazenda, andando entre a borda da mata e pasto. Entramos na área da pousada em trecho de campina e campinara e depois pegamos a trilha que sai da campina, beira o rio e termina na pousada. Na companhia dos amigos e clientes Arjan Dawarshuis e Ies Goedbloed.

Spectacle of hundreds of parrots/parakeets descending onto the exposed rocks around the waterfall to feed of the algae. Truly spectacular but seems to be seasonal, as this was seen during July. In October and January when we returned a 2nd and 3rd time it was not seen again.

trip_comments: With Diana Hews and our Cristalino Jungle Lodge guide, Jorge.  Birded briefly on lodge grounds, then cross river to the Serra trail.  Stayed along river rather than climbing to ridge.  At noon, we returned to the lodge for lunch and rest.  Jorge arranged a raft trip after lunch, taking a zodiac rubber raft ("la canoa") on the skiff, motoring upstream, then letting us float down to the lodge dock, a few miles.  River was about 30 meters wide.  Dense forest veetation grew right to the bank, and few rocks were exposed.  Reached dock at sunset.

locality: Rio Cristalino--general area and historical lists
trip_comments: With Diana Hews and our guide, Jorge.  First to the 50-meter tall metal tower; climbed to top and observed until 9 am. Then birding in the cool understory.  After lunch, I went to the dock to sun and cool off in river, meeting Mark and Karen Pretti, who pointed out a few birds.  Met Jorge again at 3 pm, embarked in a boat, landed in "mata de igapo" habitat, where a lake forms in thewet season.  Certain birds more likely here.  Found an army ant colony (for third consecutive day). Birded from boat on river at sunset, dusk, first half-hour of darkness.  Last full day at lodge.
Passarinhando na companhia do do meu grande amigo, Andre De Luca.

trip_comments: Don waited at boat launch very early to see Rufous-sided Crake, and then walked Castanheira Trail (730-1030) while Rita walked Main Trail (6:30-10:30) and had Collared Anteater, Brocket Deer, and a tinamou). Around lunch we visited again with Braulio Carlos & his tour; a Gray-breast Crake got trapped in one of the guy''s bathroom and was caught by Braulio for in-hand photos & then released; in afternoon Don walked Haffner Trail again (this time alone). Rita stayed around Lodge & Main Trail, had Collared Anteater again, plus Spider Monkey, Silvery Marmoset, Agouti. Don had Brocket Deer. Friate is gone and it is hot all day again
